		<header>
			
			<h1>There is a diversity of views on the EC plan to end discards</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At a hearing organised by the Fisheries Commissioner to present her plan to ban discards, attended by representatives of fishing organisations and NGOs, some members of the fishing industry opposed the plans, while others suggested that the proposals should be modified.</p><p>On her blog, the Commissioner wrote: ‘The approach of all the participants in the event, finally, was very constructive, aimed at defining the solution to a problem that we all want to tackle. It is clear that the first and foremost goal must be to avoid discards, to avoid catching what we do not want to. Bearing this in mind, we can then work out together solutions to make the best use out of those by-catches that will still be unavoidable in European fisheries, which are very often mixed … But there is no one-size-fits-all solution: European fisheries have their own peculiarities and fishermen’s culture is not the same in all EU countries. For this, we need mechanisms adapted to geographical areas and type of fisheries. In addition, as we cannot have as many ships controlling that the ban is respected [sic], as the fishing vessels at sea, we need fishermen to take ownership of the reform and be the first ones wanting it to be effective. So we need a gradual approach and the right incentives for the fishing sector’.</p><p>But fishermen are currently concerned that they will lose money as a result of a ban, mainly because they will be forced to land lower-value fish for which there is little consumer demand. Sections of the fishing industry and some member states have come up with an alternative proposal that would water down the Commission's plans. Under this alternative, discards would not be banned outright but would rely on fishermen signing up voluntarily: those who land their discards would be rewarded by receiving a bigger quota.</p><p>However, conservationists opposed this proposal. Greenpeace said that if it was adopted, fishermen who discarded the most would receive a higher catch quota: ‘It is ridiculous to reward the fishermen that discard the most with a higher catch quota unless there is an effort to shift towards more selective fishing methods. Unbelievably, destructive bottom trawlers with high levels of discards would get more out of this scheme than fishermen using sustainable fishing methods.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
EC Commissioner for Fisheries and Maritime Affairs, blog, 4 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://blogs.ec.europa.eu/damanaki/a-dialogue-for-ending-discards/" target="_self">http://blogs.ec.europa.eu/damanaki/a-dialogue-for-ending-discards/</a><br />
Press article, <i>The Guardian</i>, 3 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2011/may/03/fishing-industry-eu-discards-plan" target="_self">http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2011/may/03/fishing-industry-eu-di...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Coastal ACP countries are facing similar challenges, as many fleets fishing in their EEZs have significant levels of discards, due both to the use of unselective fishing gears and high-grading (discarding fish of lower commercial value due to limited space on board). The current debate in the EU shows how difficult it will be to implement a measure like a discard ban. Whatever measure is finally applied to EU fleets will also have to be appropriately translated for EU fleets fishing in ACP or international waters. A discard ban, and the compulsory landing of all their catches, may be even more difficult to implement for those fleets which do not always land locally and stay at sea, in some cases for weeks or months at a time. A more realistic solution would be to ensure that only vessels using selective fishing practices, and which therefore avoid most by-catch, are allowed to fish in third-country waters. Promoting local landings in ACP countries would also enable these fleets to land all their catches in local ports, which might also help to diminish the levels of high-grading practised.</p>
		</div>
		
